1
00:00:02,359 --> 00:00:05,939
You now have a basic understanding of probability. Great job!

2
00:00:05,940 --> 00:00:09,824
Let's quickly summarize what was covered in this lesson.

3
00:00:09,824 --> 00:00:12,059
You learned about the probability of an event.

4
00:00:12,060 --> 00:00:14,245
Such as the outcome of a coin flip.

5
00:00:14,244 --> 00:00:15,599
You learned that the probability of

6
00:00:15,599 --> 00:00:19,769
the opposite event is one minus the probability of this event.

7
00:00:19,769 --> 00:00:22,890
And you learned about the probability of a composite event,

8
00:00:22,890 --> 00:00:27,375
which was in the form of P times P times P and so on.

9
00:00:27,375 --> 00:00:29,634
This rule is true because the events we've

10
00:00:29,635 --> 00:00:32,325
observed so far are independent of one another,

11
00:00:32,325 --> 00:00:36,910
which means the outcome of one event doesn't affect the outcome of another,

12
00:00:36,909 --> 00:00:40,649
which is also the case in the next lesson on binomial distributions.

13
00:00:40,649 --> 00:00:44,189
However, if we're looking at the probability of dependent events,

14
00:00:44,189 --> 00:00:49,170
say the probability of rain tomorrow given that it rained today, this rule doesn't hold.

15
00:00:49,170 --> 00:00:52,704
Dependent events where the outcomes of later events depend

16
00:00:52,704 --> 00:00:56,234
on what has already happened are at the heart of the following topics,

17
00:00:56,234 --> 00:00:58,439
unconditional probability and Bayes Rule.

